+# OctoAcme Project Management Docs
+
+Welcome to the central knowledge hub for OctoAcme project management. This folder contains living documentation that guides how we run projects, align teams, and continuously improve our delivery practices. Whether you are onboarding to the team or looking for a specific process reference, this is your starting point.
+
+## Overview of OctoAcme Project Management Processes
+
+OctoAcme uses a lightweight but structured project management approach that guides work from initiation through planning, execution, release, and retrospective improvement. Projects begin with a clear business need, success metrics, stakeholder alignment, an initial risk list, and a lightweight one-pager to support go/no-go decisions. Once approved, planning focuses on turning the initiative into an actionable backlog with acceptance criteria, estimates, dependencies, milestones, a definition of done, and an initial QA approach. This creates a repeatable lifecycle in which teams move from idea validation to delivery readiness with shared expectations and documented artifacts.
+
+The process depends on clearly defined roles working together across the project lifecycle. Project Managers coordinate delivery, schedules, risks, meetings, and stakeholder communication; Product Managers define outcomes, prioritize backlog items, and measure success; Developers implement features, contribute to estimation and planning, and help identify technical risks; QA contributors validate quality and acceptance criteria; and stakeholders provide input and approvals. OctoAcme's personas documentation reinforces these responsibilities and positions each role as part of a collaborative, cross-functional delivery model with clear ownership and accountability.
+
+Execution is managed through a regular operating rhythm and visible workflow practices. Teams use project boards with stages such as Backlog, Ready, In Progress, In Review, QA, and Done, supported by daily or frequent standups, weekly delivery or PM/Product syncs, sprint-end demos, and monthly stakeholder updates. Risks and dependencies are tracked through a risk register and discussed in weekly syncs, while escalation paths move from team-level triage to PM and Product Lead involvement and then to sponsor-level escalation for business-critical issues. Communication emphasizes a single source of truth, regular status reporting, milestone-based updates, and incident-specific communication when urgent problems arise.
+
+Quality assurance is built into both development and release practices rather than treated as a final checkpoint. During execution, teams use small pull requests when possible, include issue links and acceptance criteria in PR descriptions, run automated tests and linting in CI, and obtain at least one approval before merging. QA expectations include unit tests for new logic, integration tests where needed, end-to-end smoke tests for critical flows, security scanning in CI, and manual QA for feature acceptance when appropriate. Before release, OctoAcme requires completed acceptance criteria, passing CI and security checks, release notes, rollback planning, smoke test preparation, and post-deployment verification, followed by retrospectives that convert lessons learned into tracked improvement actions.
